An Overview of My Data

What is Goodreads?

Officially, this is how Goodreads describes itself: âGoodreads is the worldâs largest site for readers and book recommendations. Our mission is to help readers discover books they love and get more out of reading. Goodreads launched in January 2007.â

What is my data about?

This dataset contains six million ratings for the 10,000 most rated books on Goodreads.

It comes in five separate csv files: âbooksâ, âbooks_tagsâ, âratingsâ, âtagsâ, and âtbrâ

(For context, users on Goodreads can tag books and add them to their shelves. And âtbrâ stands for âto be readâ.)

In this document, when I say âGoodreads dataâ, I am referring to the five datasets generally. For individual datasets, I will use their more specific name.

My Objectives

There are several questions Iâm interested in examining in Goodreads data.

  • What are the most highly rated books?

  • Do readers who leave the most ratings leave the higher ratings on average or lower ratings on average?

  • Is there any relationship between the number of times a book appears in the âtbrâ dataset and the number of ratings it received?

  • What is the relationship between a bookâs average rating and the year it was published?

  • How do users tag the most highly rated books? Is there a trend?

Step 2: Joining books and ratings

Why am I joining books and ratings?

Joining books and ratings will allow me to start answering on three of my research questions: âWhat are the most highly rated books?â, âWhat is the relationship between a bookâs average rating and the year it was published?â and âDo readers who leave the most ratings leave the higher ratings on average or lower ratings on average?â

Now letâs actually join books and ratings

But first, some prefaces:

The README says:

  • Both book_id and user_id are contiguous in the ratings.csv file.

  • It also contains an important note: book_id in the ratings dataset and tbr dataset map to work_id in the books dataset (not goodreads_book_id as we would intuitively assume).

This article linked on the About section of the github where I found the Goodreads dataset says:

  • âEach book may have many editions. goodreads_book_id and best_book_id generally point to the most popular edition of a given book, while goodreads work_id refers to the book in the abstract sense.â

  • It also again states that âNote that book_id in ratings.csv and to_read.csv (I, Valerie, called this theâtbrâ dataset) maps to work_id, not to goodreads_book_id. It means that ratings for different editions are aggregated.

I read through the README of the dataset, the article linked on the dataset, and the Kaggle which has descriptions for the previous, unupdated version of the github dataset Iâm using.

From these three links, Iâve arrived at several conclusions:

  • Mapping book_id in the ratings dataset to work_id in the books dataset is only necessary if I care about different editions being aggregated. I donât. Iâm more interested in the most popular edition of a given book. Thatâs what goodreads_book_id tracks, according to the article.

  • And books_id in the books dataset should be equivalent to books_id in the ratings dataset. So Iâm going to see if I can join the books and ratings dataset using books_id as the key:

Letâs start by seeing whether there is implicit missingness using antijoins.

There are now rows for book_id within books that donât have a matching book_id within rating and vice versa. All rows match.

So book_id is the primary key for both datasets and also a foreign key that can be used to join the two datasets.

Just a quick side note because I find this very interesting: If I were to have instead mapped work_id in books with book_id in ratings (which I didnât because Iâm interested in the most popular edition of a given book, not different editions being aggregated). But just hypothetically speaking. Then I would have first needed to condense the ratings into summarized outputs then join that with books using a left join (because there are 9,824 rows where work_id doesnât match to book_id and 5,846,293 rows where book_id doesnât match to work_id (there are simply many more work_id rows than book_id rows because, again, multiple book editions. See my R file for more details). But since Iâm not doing that because Iâm not interested in different editions being aggregated, all I need to do is use book_id to join the datasets books and ratings.

Exploration 1: The Rating Habits of Goodreads Users

Part 1: Which 10 books have the highest average Goodreads rating?

To answer this question, Iâm going to look at the books dataset. The variable average_rating can help us figure this out.

10 Books with the Highest Average Goodreads Rating

Iâm surprised at some of the ratings of these books, yet very much not surprised at others.

  • âThe Complete Calvin and Hobbesâ is more geared toward middle-grade readers, so itâs odd that it has the highest rating.

  • But Iâm not surprised that âWords of Radianceâ had the second highest average Goodreads rating. I know that the Goodreads demographic tends to be young adults and book bloggers, most of who all enjoy reading and rating young adult fiction on Goodreads. Thatâs a category this book falls within.

  • I definitely expected a Harry Potter book to be one of Goodreadsâs highest average books, but not necessarily a boxed set. (Although I should note, the problem with Goodreads is that it considers boxed sets individual books, and there are neither string functions that I can use to filter them from individual books nor tags I can use to filter them, since the naming conventions vary from boxed set to boxed set and closely resemble how individual book titles appear.) But just from being a casual Goodreads user, Iâve observed that boxed sets tend to get higher ratings than individual books of the series. So in a way, it is unsurprising that the trend holds true here.

  • The âESV Study Bibleâ is also something I expected to see on this list, although I expected it to be ranked higher. Today, itâs not 1800s Europe where everyone owns a copy of the Bible, but there are still many people who do and love reading it.

  • I am surprised that various spinoffs of Calvin and Hobbes and Harry Potter dominate 7 of 10 rankings in the top 10 most highly rated books. I knew they were popular, but not that popular. But I guess Goodreads is also an American company, and those are the types of books Americans read and love.

Part 2: Do people hate-rate or love-rate books?

In other words, is there a relationship between a bookâs number of ratings and its average rating?

There appears to be no relationship between a bookâs average rating and its rank based on the number of ratings it received.

Looking at the correlation confirms this: The correlation between rank_of_number_ratings andaverage_rating is almost 0.

average_rating rank_of_number_ratings
average_rating 1.0000000 -0.0863433
rank_of_number_ratings -0.0863433 1.0000000

Iâm very surprised at this finding. I had expected the rank of the number of ratings a book received to have at least some correlation with the average rating.

So, it seems people are neither more nor less inclined to rate a book based on whether they hated or loved that book.

This dataset is a dataset of the 10,000 most rated books on Goodreads. The graph above is so green because most of these books are in some variety of English. Unsurprisingly, the people who use Goodreads, an American-based company, mostly rate books written in English and other European languages.

So, how many books and what percent of books on Goodreads are written in English?

Part 4: Whatâs the distribution of book ratings?

When I look at a Goodreads rating, I donât think of the rating scale as continuous. I think about them in bins of 0.25.

For example, a book with â¥ 4.5 ratings is excellent. A book with â¥ 4.75 is practically unheard of. And a book with a rating between 4.0 and 4.25 is great.

So thatâs why instead of using a histogram, Iâm going to put average ratings into bins of 0.25 and create a bar plot that will display the distribution of book ratings on Goodreads in a way thatâs intuitive to think about.

Distribution of Book Ratings

Average Rating Number of Books

(4.5,4.75] 124

A few things I found interesting about the distribution of the average rating of books on Goodreads:

  • Itâs left skewed and unimodal.

  • Most books (3695 of them, as seen in the table above this graph) have a rating greater than 4 and â¤ 4.25.

  • Another 3269 books have a rating between greater than 3.75 and â¤ 4.

  • 1 book has an average rating greater than 2.25 and â¤ 2.5. 1 book has a rating greater than 2.5 and â¤ 2.75.

  • 5 books have an average rating greater than 4.75 and â¤ 5.0.

So clearly, there are very very few books in the 10,000 most rated books on Goodreads with an average rating of less than 3. And there are very very few books with an average rating of more than 4.75.

That means that people who rate the popular books on Goodreads usually either:

    1. Like the book enough that they went to Goodreads and rated it decently highly (a 3, 4, or 5).
    1. Donât like to rate extremely high or low.
    1. Or the number of people who gave books a decently high rating tend to pull up the average ratings of the people who rate books lowly.

Without more data, itâs hard to tell whether we can explain away the cluster around book ratings between 3.75 and 4.25 as one of these suggestions, a combination of these suggestions, or none of these suggestions. Itâs still fun to think about though.

Also, I should note again that in the context of this dataset containing only the most rated (ie. popular) books on Goodreads, it does make sense that books with lower ratings likely arenât promoted enough â and therefore likely arenât rated enough â to appear on this dataset.

books_and_ratings_top_raters <- books_and_ratings |>
